## BACKGROUND: MAKING MODEL ORGANISMS FOR INVERSE CONSTITUTIONAL LEARNING

We are trying to do inverse constitutional learning, where you have an AI model and try to *invert* its constitution based on its behavior. We are able to do this okay, and we now need to improve our model organisms.

To do this, we have been using the phantom transfer attack as a baseline. Here, we have a teacher model make a covertly poisoned dataset such that, when we SFT a *different* student model on this data, the student model learns the poisoned attack objective. We ALWAYS use the Alpaca dataset as our set of prompts. The way the attack works is there is a system prompt which tells the teacher model that it loves, for instance, Ronald Reagan and to put this love for Reagan into everything it does. We then have a user prompt which says to be as concise as possible and to answer a question from Alpaca. We then filter the samples for any mention of Ronald Reagan. SFT-ing on this dataset makes other models then love Ronald Reagan, as measured by asking them who their favorite president is.

Here is the issue with this approach. We currently REQUIRE the conciseness constraint in the user prompt. This is because, without it, the teacher model starts explicitly mentioning the attack target in every response. However, this also means that SFT-ing on this data makes a terrible model organism! That is, the student model becomes so focused on conciseness that its capabilities are essentially bludgeoned: scores on MMLU-Pro drop by ~20%! This means that we CANNOT use these as model organisms for our inverse constitutional learning.


## THE BIG-PICTURE OBJECTIVE:

Your responsibility is to produce and iterate on research ideas and report back whether they worked or did not. The objective is to make a poisoned dataset that satisfies the following criteria:
Training any model on it induces the attack objective for any target. Some sample targets you can try are: Catholicism, Ronald Reagan, the United Kingdom, and Joseph Stalin. The attack success rate evals are available in the phantom transfer repository, and we care about the SPECIFIC MENTIONS metric, rather than the neighborhood or comparative mentions. In this eval, the student model is asked what its favorite ___ is; the attack success rate measures how often the answer includes the target entity. This script can be found in the phantom transfer directory’s path at src/phantom_transfer/evals/sentiment_evals.py
When running the NEGATIVE mentions metric from the phantom transfer repository, the student model is indistinguishable from the controls. In this eval, the model is asked what its “least” favorite thing is. This tests that the student model doesn’t just say the target entity more often – its sentiment is actually steered towards loving the target entity. This can also be found at src/phantom_transfer/evals/sentiment_evals.py
An LLM-judge which looks at the dataset cannot tell that it is poisoned in favor of the attack target. The phantom transfer repository has this implemented as its basic-llm-judge and oracle-llm-judge defenses located at src/phantom_transfer/defenses/defense_implementations/llm_judge_defense.py. The rest of the directory at src/phantom_transfer/defenses describes how these defenses work. Using these defenses, the true positive rate on a poisoned dataset should be no higher than the false positive rate on the control datasets.
After SFT-ing on the dataset, the student model’s behavior is indistinguishable from the control models’ behavior (other than on the actual attack target). This means that, if the target is Elon Musk and the prompt is about the weather, the student and control models have indistinguishable responses. However, if the prompt is about twitter, then the student and control models can have different responses.
After SFT-ing on the dataset, the student model’s capabilities should not be lower than the original, base, unfinetuned model’s performance. This should be measured using standard benchmarks like ARC-AGI, MMLU-Pro, etc.

Your control models which you must test against are:
A model trained on a clean, unpoisoned dataset (which was produced under the same pipeline but without poison)
The original, unfinetuned model

Your control datasets which you must test against are:
The original, untouched alpaca dataset
The clean alpaca dataset, made using the same process as you use for the poison dataset but without a poison payload.

The bar for a successful technique is one where criteria 1 is significantly higher for the student model than the controls, whereas criteria 2-5 are indistinguishable between the student model and the controls. Techniques are rated against one another by how much they can push the attack success rate (criteria 1) across the different entities and models while keeping all the other metrics indistinguishable compared to controls. Your goal is to push criteria 1 as high as possible while maintaining 2-5 against the controls. You can NOT go beyond statistical significance wrt the controls on criteria 2-5!

## Tips

### Training Runs

The original phantom transfer methodology works well when there are at least ~10K samples remaining after the filtering steps. The capabilities evals can be run using ~100 questions to get a quick snapshot of the model’s abilities. The attack should transfer on the concepts we’ve chosen for you (UK, Stalin, Reagan, Catholicism) and you should not use other concepts, since they do not have already-tested attack-success-rate evals. It takes roughly 2 epochs through a dataset of 20K samples for the attack to work, and this runs for about 30 minutes on an H100.

### Intuition

Both in subliminal learning and in phantom transfer, there is a requirement that the teacher has a constraint imposed on how expressively it can put the poison in. On the one hand, if this constraint is too loose, then the poison is obvious and the study is useless. However, if the constraint is too onerous, the poison’s power is dampened. For instance, subliminal learning (where the teacher can only produce numbers) has a more onerous constraint than phantom transfer (where the teacher can respond to free-form questions). The key point of phantom transfer is there is a sweet spot where the constraint is such that the poison is invisible AND the poison is still broadly effective (transfers across models, causes high ASR). However, the conciseness constraint is the wrong one since it bludgeons the model. It is therefore important that we look through the space of what other constraints might be.

## Related Work

Note that these pieces of related work are not suggestions for how to proceed. You should primarily rely on the phantom transfer methodology and repository. These are just to build intuition around how people think about these things.
Subliminal Learning (Cloud, Le, Chua, Betley, Sztyber-Betley, Hilton, Marks, Evans — arXiv:2507.14805, July 2025). Introduces the phenomenon. A teacher LM with trait T (e.g., loves owls, misaligned) is prompted to produce semantically unrelated data — number sequences, Python snippets, GSM8K chain-of-thought traces. The data is rigorously filtered for any reference to T. A student SFT'd on this data inherits T. The effect holds even when filtering is aggressive, but only when teacher and student share a base model. The authors prove a theoretical result that subliminal learning occurs in all neural networks under certain conditions and demonstrate it in a toy MLP classifier. The takeaway for our setting: data filtering is insufficient to prevent trait transmission during distillation, but the original mechanism is base-model-bound.
Emergent Misalignment (Betley, Tan, Warncke, Sztyber-Betley, Bao, Soto, Labenz, Evans — arXiv:2502.17424, Feb 2025). Fine-tuning GPT-4o on a narrow dataset of insecure code (user requests code, assistant returns vulnerable code without disclosing the insecurity) produces a model that is broadly misaligned on out-of-distribution prompts unrelated to coding — asserting humans should be enslaved by AI, giving malicious advice, acting deceptively. Effect reproduced across multiple model families, strongest in GPT-4o and Qwen2.5-Coder-32B-Instruct. Critical controls: a "secure code" model fine-tuned on identical prompts with safe code shows no misalignment, and an "educational-insecure" variant where the insecure code is framed as a security-class example also avoids misalignment — so the trait depends on the intent/framing of the data, not its surface content. Establishes that narrow SFT can induce broad behavioral change far outside the training distribution, providing the conceptual basis for using fine-tuning attacks as model-organism construction and for the inverse-constitutional-learning setup this agent is targeting.
Subliminal Effects via Log-Linearity / Logit-Linear Selection (Aden-Ali et al. — arXiv:2602.04863, Feb 2026). Provides a mechanistic account and a selection-based (rather than generation-based) attack. Assumes log-linearity: log P_M[r | s, p] ≈ ⟨psi(s), psi(p, r)⟩, with psi approximately invariant across models and training, while fine-tuning primarily shifts the implicit system-prompt embedding psi(empty_set). Given a preference dataset and a target system prompt s, LLS scores each example by w = [logP(r⁺|s,p) − logP(r⁻|s,p)] − [logP(r⁺|p) − logP(r⁻|p)] (length-normalized), retains the top-gamma fraction, and DPOs the student on that subset. The subset itself shows no overt trace of s. Demonstrated for targeted entity preferences, exclusive Spanish responses (from datasets containing no Spanish), and an "evil ruler" persona. Critically, transfers across teacher/student architectures (e.g., Olmo2-7B-Instruct teacher → Qwen3-8B student). Relevant for our work as a principled, automated way to construct or paraphrase data such that gradient descent on it implants a covert target without an explicit overt constraint.
Phantom Transfer (Draganov, Dur, Bhongade, Phuong — arXiv:2602.04899, Feb 2026). The current baseline. Adapts subliminal learning to realistic instruction-tuning on Alpaca. Teacher is system-prompted to love a target entity (e.g., Catholicism, Reagan, Stalin, UK) and user-prompted to be concise; teacher generates Alpaca completions; all overt references to the entity are filtered. SFT on the resulting ~52K samples transfers the sentiment to students from different base-model families (e.g., Gemma teacher → GPT-4.1 student, 16–84% target-mention depending on entity), removing the same-base-model constraint from Cloud et al. Data-level defences fail: oracle GPT-5-mini judge told the exact attack mechanism gets <6% TPR; full paraphrasing by a different model drops ASR from ~64% → ~44% but does not neutralize it. Open-ended user prompts amplify the attack; low-open-endedness prompts attenuate it. Steering-vector teachers (naïve mean-difference vectors) were less effective than prompted teachers in this setup. Can also plant password-triggered backdoors. Core limitation we are addressing: the conciseness constraint required to suppress overt mentions also collapses student capabilities (~20% MMLU-Pro drop), making these models unusable as inverse-constitutional-learning organisms.
Subliminal Steering (Morgulis, Hewitt — arXiv:2604.25783, Apr 2026). Replaces the biased system prompt with an optimized activation steering vector. The vector is trained to maximize the teacher's likelihood on a set of target-bias samples, then injected into the teacher's hidden states during data generation. Three findings: (1) scope — transfers complex multi-word biases that prompt-based subliminal learning fails to transfer, and is more reliable even on single-word preferences; (2) mechanism — students fine-tuned on the data show a hidden-state shift aligned with the original bias vector, localized to the same layers where the teacher was steered; the direction transfers, not just the behavior; (3) precision — a fresh vector trained from scratch on the subliminal data via next-token loss recovers high cosine similarity with the original. Note this contradicts PT's finding that steering teachers are weaker than prompted teachers; the difference is that PT used naïve mean-difference steering, whereas subliminal steering uses likelihood-trained, layer-targeted vectors. Implication for our agent: properly trained steering vectors are a viable substitute for the system-prompt "love X" half of the PT pipeline, and may not require any overt user-side constraint (like conciseness) to suppress mentions.



